The paper deals with improving the matching performance of SIFT descriptors, which are commonly used in computer vision applications such as image matching and object recognition. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also uses a contrario methodology, which is a statistical inference technique commonly used in information retrieval and machine learning, suggesting that cs.IR (Information Retrieval) is another likely sub-category. The paper also presents a new method called meaningful clamping, which involves efficiently computing a clamping threshold unique for every descriptor, indicating that cs.LG (Machine Learning) is another possible sub-category. The paper also uses a generative uniform background model, which is a statistical model commonly used in multimedia applications, suggesting that cs.MM (Multimedia) is another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper presents a method to improve matching performance, which is a common goal in artificial intelligence applications, suggesting that cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is another possible sub-category.
